    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with **Pete Crow-Armstrong** serving as our clear offensive anchor. His score of 82.13 is driven by a massive +19% SP Skill boost against Petty, who represents our softest opposing arm of the day (xERA 6.57). Given that stolen bases are at a premium for our squad, his elite sprint speed makes him an auto-start, especially with favorable wind conditions providing a slight ceiling boost. Similarly, **Junior Caminero** (65.79) and **Trea Turner** (65.20) are high-floor pivots against Lauer and Junk, respectively; **Trea Turner** remains locked into the leadoff spot, capitalizing on high-volume opportunities, while **Junior Caminero** benefits from a strong order placement and a favorable SP xERA of 4.38.\n\nConversely, our lineup composition reflects a cautious approach to platoon disadvantages and high-end pitching. **Colt Keith** (42.94) and **Hyeseong Kim** (41.69) are teetering near our bench threshold, as both face left-handed opposition, which severely crimps their efficiency scores. While **Hyeseong Kim** gets a marginal bump due to the opposing pitcher\u2019s slow delivery\u2014a tactical edge we are exploiting to hunt stolen bases\u2014the limited upside against a lefty like Okert makes him a bottom-tier start. We reviewed potential utility depth, but with **Christian Yelich** and **Lars Nootbaar** remaining on the IL and **Caleb Durbin** absent from the confirmed starting lineup, our depth is currently constrained. We are essentially riding our active high-xwOBA producers like **Yordan Alvarez** (63.86) despite his tough matchup against Yamamoto, relying on his elite discipline to outperform the SP skill deficit. Manage your game caps closely; the delta between our top play, **Pete Crow-Armstrong**, and our marginal starters is significant enough that we may look to pull the plug on **Hyeseong Kim** if the early innings suggest a suppressed run environment.",
